      "title": "How My Blog Chatbot Ended Up Using RAG",
      "url": "/en/blog/building-ai-chat-for-my-blog#at-first-i-wanted-to-start-with-search",
      "excerpt": "I did not begin with the assumption that I needed embedding based RAG from day one. This blog is still mostly static content, and the total number of posts is not that large. I was already managing content with MDX, so…",
      "content": "At First, I Wanted to Start with Search\nI did not begin with the assumption that I needed embedding based RAG from day one. This blog is still mostly static content, and the total number of posts is not that large. I was already managing content with MDX, so in the beginning it seemed more than reasonable to build a good static search layer first. In practice, that meant something close to Pagefind: generate search records at build time, then run lexical search over those records at runtime. That approach had a few advantages I liked. First, it required no extra infrastructure. The blog already runs on Next.js, and the search index could be generated during the build. No separate database. No vector store. That alone was a large benefit. Second, the reasoning behind the results was relatively easy to explain. If a post matched, it usually matched because the title, tags, or body actually contained the relevant words. The search itself was lightweight, and the operational burden was close to zero. So at that point, it felt good enough. For a static blog, I did not think I needed to jump into a heavy AI architecture immediately.",
