      "excerpt": "The reason I wanted embedding based RAG started to show up after trying a few real questions. I wanted to be less dependent on exact string matches. The system had to find the right documents even when the same meaning…",
      "content": "That Was Why I Wanted to Try Embedding-Based RAG\nThe reason I wanted embedding based RAG started to show up after trying a few real questions. I wanted to be less dependent on exact string matches. The system had to find the right documents even when the same meaning was phrased differently. It also had to gather evidence across multiple documents instead of stopping at one article. I wanted to index blog posts, about, projects, and internal assistant documents together. Otherwise it would still feel more like a search box than a chatbot for the whole site. There was still one objection I had to answer. \"Wouldn't it be more natural to just let the LLM read the documents directly?\" That question is still valid. In fact, for prompts like \"hello\", \"who are you?\", or \"what is the latest post?\", a raw LLM can sometimes sound more natural. But that approach gets more expensive as the corpus grows, because you keep pushing long context into the model. It also gives you less control over what the answer is grounded in. Once I cared about things like \"do not speak as if you are the author,\" \"only use public information,\" and \"show which post supports this answer,\" a separate retrieval laye…",
