      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "building-ai-chat-for-my-blog",
      "title": "How My Blog Chatbot Ended Up Using RAG",
      "url": "/en/blog/building-ai-chat-for-my-blog#cost-needed-its-own-track",
      "excerpt": "If you are building embedding based RAG, the first choice that comes to mind is the OpenAI embedding API. The path is familiar: embed the documents, embed the incoming query with the same model, then retrieve from there…",
      "content": "Cost Needed Its Own Track\nIf you are building embedding based RAG, the first choice that comes to mind is the OpenAI embedding API. The path is familiar: embed the documents, embed the incoming query with the same model, then retrieve from there. But in my case, the cost structure started to bother me a little. I was already using a generation model for answers, and that side felt easier to trial. At the time, the OpenAI setup I was looking at allowed up to 2.5M tokens per day across the mini family, including gpt 5.4 mini, under the data sharing program. So for answer generation I was comfortable using GPT 5.4 mini, while still putting a guardrail in the app itself and treating roughly one hundred requests as the initial trial range. Embeddings, on the other hand, create a separate cost axis: document indexing and query embedding both call the API continuously. That means the chatbot no longer has only \"answer generation cost.\" It also has a second ongoing cost line just to keep retrieval working. That mattered because the chatbot was never going to be a one time feature. I wanted to regenerate the index when new posts were added, and I wanted the freedom to rebuild it when the r…",
