      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "building-ai-chat-for-my-blog",
      "title": "How My Blog Chatbot Ended Up Using RAG",
      "url": "/en/blog/building-ai-chat-for-my-blog#that-was-why-i-moved-to-modal",
      "excerpt": "After that, I shifted the embedding endpoint to Modal. My goal was narrow. I did not want to move the blog itself. I just wanted a single endpoint dedicated to embeddings. In that sense, Modal fit what I wanted better.…",
      "content": "That Was Why I Moved to Modal\nAfter that, I shifted the embedding endpoint to Modal. My goal was narrow. I did not want to move the blog itself. I just wanted a single endpoint dedicated to embeddings. In that sense, Modal fit what I wanted better. It was easy to expose a /v1/embeddings endpoint with FastAPI, and to use the same model for both document and query embeddings. Answer generation, question routing, and result composition could stay inside Next.js. Only embedding generation moved outside. That was the boundary I wanted. The cost perspective also became easier to reason about. I could think about answer generation and embedding generation separately, and at least for me, it no longer felt like I was keeping a heavy dedicated deployment alive just for embeddings. Modal is not a perfect answer either. Cold starts still exist. But for one embedding endpoint attached to a blog at this scale, it felt lighter than the Lightning setup I had before.",
