      "excerpt": "Once embeddings enter the picture, the next question becomes where to store them. You can use pgvector, an external vector database, or something much heavier. At first, I thought all of that would be overkill for this…",
      "content": "Why I Moved the Vector Store to PostgreSQL\nOnce embeddings enter the picture, the next question becomes where to store them. You can use pgvector, an external vector database, or something much heavier. At first, I thought all of that would be overkill for this blog. The total document count was not huge, and I was already running things in a self hosted, single server environment. So in the beginning, SQLite felt perfectly reasonable. The site content is not a massive, highly dynamic corpus. It behaves more like static content that gets indexed at build time and regenerated when needed. But once I connected the chatbot to the real operating flow, a different problem showed up. This project already has a workflow where writing a post on the web eventually creates a GitHub commit, and that commit triggers redeployment. In that situation, keeping embedding output in a SQLite file quickly raised awkward questions: when should it be generated, before or after deployment, and does the generated file need to be committed again? That is why I moved the vector store into PostgreSQL with pgvector, so embeddings and retrieval metadata live inside the database instead of inside a generated f…",
