      "excerpt": "Actually building it changed the way I thought about the problem. At first, I vaguely assumed that adding embeddings would make the chatbot smarter. I do not think that anymore. Embeddings reduce phrasing mismatch and h…",
      "content": "I Had to Separate Question Types\nActually building it changed the way I thought about the problem. At first, I vaguely assumed that adding embeddings would make the chatbot smarter. I do not think that anymore. Embeddings reduce phrasing mismatch and help gather evidence across documents, but the answers still feel awkward if the question flow is not handled. So I started separating question types first. Questions like \"hello\", \"how can I contact you?\", \"what is the latest post?\", and \"what is the oldest post?\" felt more natural to handle directly than to send through retrieval. Questions like \"who are you?\", \"what kind of developer is this person?\", \"what is the main tech stack?\", and \"what design philosophy appears across this blog?\" depend much more on evidence retrieval. The current structure does not send questions straight to retrieval. It organizes the question once, then chooses the next path. Planner guided blog chatbot architecture The Question Planner in the middle is not there to force every prompt into one rigid category. It rewrites the question into something clearer, then decides whether the request can be answered directly, needs evidence retrieval, or is vague en…",
