      "id": "en/building-ai-chat-for-my-blog/closing-thoughts",
      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "building-ai-chat-for-my-blog",
      "title": "How My Blog Chatbot Ended Up Using RAG",
      "url": "/en/blog/building-ai-chat-for-my-blog#closing-thoughts",
      "excerpt": "The biggest reason I built this chatbot, honestly, was that I had been getting more interested in RAG lately. After spending time with products like NotebookLM, I found the experience of reading documents and answering…",
      "content": "Closing Thoughts\nThe biggest reason I built this chatbot, honestly, was that I had been getting more interested in RAG lately. After spending time with products like NotebookLM, I found the experience of reading documents and answering with grounded context genuinely compelling. At some point, it stopped feeling enough to just use someone else's product. I wanted to try building that experience into my own blog. Once I started, the work went beyond whether search was enough or how far embeddings should go. Tone, evidence boundaries, deployment flow, and indexing all came along with it. I do not think this structure is the final form. But the path from static search to Lightning AI, and then to Modal + PostgreSQL, now makes much more sense to me than it did at the start.",
