      "url": "/en/blog/leemage-case-study#how-leemage-grew-from-a-cost-problem-into-a-file-management-platform",
      "excerpt": "When building side projects, file uploads usually get pushed to the end. You start with authentication, deployment, payments, and the product flow users see first, and only later think, \"I should probably support image…",
      "content": "How Leemage Grew from a Cost Problem into a File Management Platform\nWhen building side projects, file uploads usually get pushed to the end. You start with authentication, deployment, payments, and the product flow users see first, and only later think, \"I should probably support image uploads too.\" I used to treat uploads as a minor feature as well. But after repeating the same pattern across multiple projects, my perspective changed. The moment image uploads entered the picture, cost became a very practical issue. The feature itself looks small, but depending on the service you choose, fixed costs show up sooner than expected. That makes the problem awkward for side projects. Building it yourself feels tedious, but paying for an external SaaS every time also feels wasteful. At that point, I kept coming back to one question: Do I really have to solve this problem with a paid service every single time? That was when OCI Object Storage and Cloudflare R2 became interesting options. Both provide enough free tier capacity for the scale I had in mind, and they felt realistic enough to build around. So instead of choosing a fully managed service like Cloudinary, I decided to move towar…",
