      "excerpt": "What surprised me while building Leemage was how quickly cost concerns turned into performance concerns as well. Image conversion shows this well. Instead of storing and serving a heavy PNG as is, converting it to WebP…",
      "content": "I Started with Cost, but Ended Up Caring about Performance Too\nWhat surprised me while building Leemage was how quickly cost concerns turned into performance concerns as well. Image conversion shows this well. Instead of storing and serving a heavy PNG as is, converting it to WebP reduces both storage usage and transfer size. That change affects storage cost, bandwidth cost, and the speed users experience at the same time. 10GB Cost Comparison If you imagine storing around 10GB of files, the difference between a typical paid storage setup and a free tier centered structure becomes hard to ignore. That gap was the original motivation behind Leemage. In side projects, even when traffic is not huge, repeated uploads and a growing image library start creating cost pressure sooner than expected. I wanted a structure where that cost could be managed instead of merely accepted. PNG vs WebP Reduction The size reduction from converting PNG to WebP also mattered in practice. The Google WebP documentation explains that lossless WebP images can be about 26% smaller than PNG. The exact number depends on the image and encoding setup, but that pattern was enough to care about. Once upload become…",
      "sectionTitle": "I Started with Cost, but Ended Up Caring about Performance Too",
