      "title": "How Leemage Grew from a Cost Problem into a File Management Platform",
      "url": "/en/blog/leemage-case-study#the-moment-it-started-feeling-like-a-reusable-foundation",
      "excerpt": "Leemage started to feel less like an internal tool and more like an actual product once I reused it in other projects. Reusing a previously built upload flow makes a bigger difference than it sounds. It means a new proj…",
      "content": "The Moment It Started Feeling Like a Reusable Foundation\nLeemage started to feel less like an internal tool and more like an actual product once I reused it in other projects. Reusing a previously built upload flow makes a bigger difference than it sounds. It means a new project does not have to redesign uploads from scratch, and it can start with storage paths, URL rules, file lifecycle management, and deletion behavior already defined. In practice, I also used Leemage as a storage adapter in another side project called leesfield. That was when the benefit felt real. I did not have to choose an upload approach again, define URL rules again, or rebuild deletion behavior from scratch. The same upload feature becomes more useful when it removes things I would otherwise repeat in the next project. Once an API is open to outside consumers, even a small mismatch between docs and behavior becomes painful. That is why I did not want OpenAPI to be a separate documentation chore. I kept the spec, the web docs, and the SDK sync flow tied together.",
      "sectionTitle": "The Moment It Started Feeling Like a Reusable Foundation",
