      "excerpt": "When people talk about building software with AI agents, the phrase harness engineering comes up more and more often. At first it sounded a little grandiose to me. But after repeatedly working with AI coding assistants,…",
      "content": "Why I Started Building Work Structure Before Asking AI to Code\nWhen people talk about building software with AI agents, the phrase harness engineering comes up more and more often. At first it sounded a little grandiose to me. But after repeatedly working with AI coding assistants, it started to feel like a very precise description. When I work with AI coding assistants, the same model can feel sharp in one repo and lost in another. The difference is often not the model. It is whether the repo tells the assistant where the docs are, what rules to follow, what stage the work is in, and what should happen next. That is why the word harness started to make sense to me. AI Harness Structure That thought came up again while reading about spec driven development. Defining the problem before implementation, recording decisions, and leaving the work status visible are useful when people work together. With AI, they show up in daily work more quickly. A person can sometimes fill in missing context from experience. An assistant often treats that missing context as room to drift. lee spec kit started from that problem. I built it as a CLI to create the docs skeleton quickly and keep feature…",
