      "locale": "en",
      "slug": "why-i-built-lee-spec-kit",
      "title": "Why I Started Building Work Structure Before Asking AI to Code",
      "url": "/en/blog/why-i-built-lee-spec-kit#but-i-wanted-it-to-fit-my-workflow",
      "excerpt": "At the same time, I wanted to shrink that idea into something that fit the way I actually work. I needed a CLI that could be applied lightly and quickly. The feature level flow still had to be visible, and the documenta…",
      "content": "But I Wanted It to Fit My Workflow\nAt the same time, I wanted to shrink that idea into something that fit the way I actually work. I needed a CLI that could be applied lightly and quickly. The feature level flow still had to be visible, and the documentation structure had to stay lightweight without becoming vague for AI. At this point, a natural question follows: \"Why not use an existing tool?\" Someone could reasonably think of options like oh my opencode. That is a fair question. But I wanted to design a harness for my own working context, not adopt another general purpose AI development tool and stop there. I did not want to remain only a user who knows how to use good tools. I wanted to work directly on the question of how to structure my own work system. lee spec kit came out of that choice. Tailored Workflow System",
