      "excerpt": "Surviving One Year as an Ordinary Developer After transferring into the Department of Computer Science, I graduated in February 2024 and joined a company a few months later. At that point, I was fairly confident in myse…",
      "content": "Surviving One Year as an Ordinary Developer\nSurviving One Year as an Ordinary Developer After transferring into the Department of Computer Science, I graduated in February 2024 and joined a company a few months later. At that point, I was fairly confident in myself. I had built up decent grades, joined several contests, and gained what I thought was practical experience through projects. I basically wanted to become a frontend developer, but I was also interested in backend and AI, so I tried to show that range during interviews and training. Maybe because of that, I ended up joining my team as a server side developer. At the time, I thought a developer was someone who solves problems, not someone tied too narrowly to one language or one way of working. So while moving into an unfamiliar area was not exactly easy, it did not feel especially frightening either.",
