      "url": "/en/blog/surviving-one-year-as-an-ordinary-developer#what-it-means-to-survive-as-an-ordinary-developer",
      "excerpt": "The last year was not full of dramatic achievements. Still, it changed how I see problems and how I work with other people. As a student, I thought growth meant building more features and handling more difficult technol…",
      "content": "What It Means to Survive as an Ordinary Developer\nThe last year was not full of dramatic achievements. Still, it changed how I see problems and how I work with other people. As a student, I thought growth meant building more features and handling more difficult technologies. Now I think growth also means asking which problem should be solved first, and organizing that problem in a way other people can understand and work with. Developers often say that the local world and the deployed world are different. For me, the last year was also about learning that building alone in a room and building as part of a team are very different worlds. I may still be an ordinary developer. Still, I now think more about making work last inside a team than about making something clever on my own.",
