      "url": "/en/blog/optimistic-update#optimistic-updates",
      "excerpt": "Optimistic Updates allow us to immediately change the query data to reflect the expected result when the mutate is successful. According to the official documentation, the difference when using likes as an example is as…",
      "content": "Optimistic Updates\nOptimistic Updates allow us to immediately change the query data to reflect the expected result when the mutate is successful. According to the official documentation, the difference when using likes as an example is as follows: Let's take a look at the actual implementation code. First, in the onMutate callback, we cancel the query using cancelQueries. Through this process, if an update occurs for that query key during the mutate, it will not be reflected. Then, we modify the existing data to create the expected result. In the example code, we used the immutability management library immer to modify the object. Now, when we apply the modified result to the corresponding query key, it will be updated as if the server had responded. Additionally, if an error occurs, we can roll back to the previous query data, and on success, we can overwrite the data with the actual response. Alternatively, there is also a method to re fetch regardless of the outcome using onSettled.",
