      "title": "Lessons Learned from Conducting a Small-Scale Project",
      "url": "/en/blog/after-toy-project#how-should-meetings-be-conducted",
      "excerpt": "To move away from the haphazard meetings , I started looking into other projects. Among them, I found the retrospective of Teo's Sprint, which was conducted based on Google Sprint, particularly interesting, and I applie…",
      "content": "How Should Meetings Be Conducted?\nTo move away from the haphazard meetings , I started looking into other projects. Among them, I found the retrospective of Teo's Sprint, which was conducted based on Google Sprint, particularly interesting, and I applied it to our work. icebreaking idea Although there are originally more steps, I condensed the process into three stages: Canvas → Idea Sketch → Implementation. In the Team Canvas, we conduct light ice breaking by allowing team members to freely jot down their thoughts. In the Idea Sketch, we write down ideas and select the final idea through presentations and voting. During Implementation, we discussed how to visualize each feature based on the ideas to finalize the implementation. Following this process naturally led us to one result. Regardless of the final implementation, I observed that all team members were satisfied with the outcome of introducing this process.",
